text:
: On successful completion of both modules, students will be
able to:
• Make links between events and facts from French current affairs and the wider
French Societal and economic framework outlined during the course;
• Follow lectures on these topics in French and take notes using an outline of the lecture;
• Read, identify and understand the structure and main points of French textbooks
and articles from specialized periodicals and newspapers on the above topics;
• Read the same materials to locate and retrieve specific information;
• Understand a French native speaker presenting factual information on these topics;
• Discuss these topics with a French native speaker; make short and structured
oral Presentations on aspects of French society and the French economy;
• Use authentic sources and course materials to develop their vocabulary and other
language competencies;
• Describe, compare and contrast the situation in France and Ireland in the context
of a discussion with French native speakers

On successful completion of this module, students should be able to:
134
· Understand and apply more complex features of German grammar, including participial
phrases and passive voice, in spoken and written contexts;
· Understand and use appropriately the specialist vocabulary (Universität) and the lexical
and syntactic features of a particular field of study (Fachsprache);
· Read and understand articles from academic publications and translate extracts into
correct and idiomatic English;
· Identify the syntactic and structural differences between oral and written language and
Fachsprache;
· Clearly summarize texts and express opinion on general topics;
· Write essays in German on a topic from their field of study;
· Give oral presentations in German on a topic from their field of study.

:
On successful completion of these modules students will be able to:
- - use Polish to express information about themselves and others, tell a story, express an
- opinion;
- - use Polish in the classroom;
- - use the case system and the verbal system at the basic level;
- - express the following meanings: quantity (how many?), time (when?), frequency (how
- often?), direction (where?)
- comprehend and extract main points from Polish-language texts, correctly identify the
general idea of a text;
- comprehend contextual information (people, places and events) in Polish-language texts;
- use reference tools (dictionaries and grammars) to obtain grammatical and lexical
information;
- formulate questions about structures they do not understand.

:
On successful completion of the modules students should be able to:
1. pursue their communicative aims through the medium of Russian;
2. use Russian for communicative purposes;
3. distinguish between different language registers and style;
4. read and comprehend moderately complex texts in Russian.

:
142
On successful completion of this module students will be able to:
- use spoken and written Polish inside and outside the classroom;
- use the case and verbal system;
- develop their understanding of how the Polish language works;
- develop their language skills (listening, reading, writing and speaking) necessary to pursue
their interests through the medium of Polish;
- develop their vocabulary related to various areas.
